Task 1: Secure the sudoers file using visudo
Subtask 1.1: Understanding the Current sudo Configuration
First, let's examine the current sudo configuration and understand the default setup.

Step 1: Check the current sudo version and basic information

sudo --version
Step 2: Display the current effective sudo configuration

sudo -l
Step 3: Examine the main sudoers file location and permissions

ls -la /etc/sudoers
Step 4: Check for additional sudoers configuration files

ls -la /etc/sudoers.d/
Subtask 1.2: Using visudo to Edit the sudoers File Safely
The visudo command is the only safe way to edit the sudoers file because it performs syntax checking before saving changes.

Step 1: Open the sudoers file with visudo

sudo visudo
Step 2: Understand the default sudoers file structure by examining these key sections:

# User privilege specification
root    ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL

# Members of the admin group may gain root privileges
%admin ALL=(ALL) ALL

# Allow members of group sudo to execute any command
%sudo   ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL
Step 3: Add security-focused configurations to the sudoers file. Navigate to the end of the file and add:

# Security hardening configurations
Defaults    env_reset
Defaults    mail_badpass
Defaults    secure_path="/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin"
Defaults    use_pty
Defaults    log_input, log_output
Defaults    iolog_dir=/var/log/sudo-io
Defaults    logfile=/var/log/sudo.log
Defaults    timestamp_timeout=15
Defaults    passwd_tries=3
Defaults    passwd_timeout=5
Step 4: Save and exit the editor. If using nano, press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter. If using vim, press Esc, type :wq, and press Enter.

