Task 3: Configure logging for sudo commands
Subtask 3.1: Setting Up Comprehensive sudo Logging
Step 1: Create the sudo log directory with proper permissions

sudo mkdir -p /var/log/sudo-io
sudo chmod 750 /var/log/sudo-io
sudo chown root:adm /var/log/sudo-io
Step 2: Verify the logging configuration in the main sudoers file

sudo visudo
Ensure these lines are present:

Defaults    logfile=/var/log/sudo.log
Defaults    log_input, log_output
Defaults    iolog_dir=/var/log/sudo-io
Defaults    syslog=auth
Defaults    syslog_goodpri=info
Defaults    syslog_badpri=alert
Step 3: Create a custom rsyslog configuration for sudo

sudo nano /etc/rsyslog.d/50-sudo.conf
Step 4: Add the following content to the rsyslog configuration:

# Log sudo commands to separate file
:programname, isequal, "sudo" /var/log/sudo-commands.log
& stop

# Log authentication events
auth,authpriv.*                 /var/log/auth.log
Step 5: Restart rsyslog to apply the new configuration

sudo systemctl restart rsyslog
Subtask 3.2: Configuring Log Rotation
Step 1: Create a logrotate configuration for sudo logs

sudo nano /etc/logrotate.d/sudo
Step 2: Add the following logrotate configuration:

/var/log/sudo.log /var/log/sudo-commands.log {
    weekly
    missingok
    rotate 52
    compress
    delaycompress
    notifempty
    create 640 root adm
    postrotate
        /usr/lib/rsyslog/rsyslog-rotate
    endscript
}

/var/log/sudo-io/*/*.log {
    weekly
    missingok
    rotate 12
    compress
    delaycompress
    notifempty
    create 640 root adm
}
Step 3: Test the logrotate configuration

sudo logrotate -d /etc/logrotate.d/sudo
